* So the correct range would be considered to be this range, 10, all close would be outside of it. So, the correct answer, this answer would be judged as incorrect, and the computation would have to done a little more careful.  
  
## Does a micro Ampere matter? (slide 77)  
* Now let me return to our original subject. You could say, does a microampere really matter? After all the amount of electricity, the current required to light a lamp, a normal household lamp, is about one ampere. A microampere, is only one millionth that much. Ten nanoamperes is only 1 100th of that millionth that is indeed a tiny amount, does it really matter?  
* Okay look at the picture, will it really matter when this thumb goes into that mouth? Will it really matter? When this thumb goes into that mouth. Will there be a response? Does it make a difference? Well there you have it. When you figure out the answer to that question you'll know the answer to the question on the slide.  
  
